<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/781"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_781_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=5a91c70508a63d33cb55879214ff67f3&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Judith Bishop" title="Judith Bishop" border="0" width="120" height="112" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/781">ECS graduate receives top scientific accolade</a></h3><p>Professor Judith Bishop, graduate of the School of Electronics and Computer Science, has been named Distinguished Woman Scientist of the Year in South Africa. Professor Bishop is both a graduate of ECS, having received her PhD in the 1970s, and a former member of staff, who taught in the School in the 1980s and 1990s. She is now based in the Department of Computer Science at the University of Pretoria, and works on frameworks for distributed systems that prolong the lifetime of highly expensive software by enabling machine-dependent components to be monitored, identified and exchanged.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/780"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_780_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=60f6d7bc4404f4bb65a8b5eccea82e9f&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="120" height="79" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/780">Technology to improve offside decisions</a></h3><p>A final-year undergraduate computer science student has come up with a proposal to tag football players in an effort to improve the accuracy of offside decisions.</p><p>While watching a football match, Jonathan Dunne, who has just completed his MEng in Computer Science at the School of Electronics and Computer Science, grew increasingly frustrated with rulings made by the Referee's Assistant and decided to base his final-year research project on how technology could be used to improve the accuracy of offside decisions.</p><p></p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/774"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_774_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=2830765af329901372ec084228a4f868&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Hugh Davis and Sue White" title="Hugh Davis and Sue White (Copyright: David Whitcher)" border="0" width="120" height="85" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/774">Multimedia Systems Course wins University teaching award</a></h3><p>Dr Hugh Davis and Su White have been awarded a Vice-Chancellor’s Teaching Award 2005 from the University of Southampton for their innovative Multimedia Systems final-year course in Computer Science on both the BSc and MEng programmes. The prize was formally awarded by the Vice-Chancellor at the ECS Graduation Ceremony on Thursday 28 July.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/767"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_767_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=7d648652e812c502b1a7280301ffc282&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="120" height="80" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/767">Network aims to advance memories for life</a></h3><p>As computers become capable of storing a lifetime's worth of memories and researchers explore prosthetic memories for humans, scientists at the University of Southampton have set up a network to develop a better understanding of how memory works and how it might be augmented by technological developments. One of the principal investigators is Professor Nigel Shadbolt from ECS.</p><p></p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050820005559/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
